 through the Bernstein Initiative. The goal of this initial phase of the center was to establish lasting structures in computational neuroscience in T√ºbingen and build a lively community bridging the gap between experimental neuroscience and machine learning. Read more Neurorobotics In future, three projects at the University of T√ºbingen will be funded by the Neurobotics research programme of the Baden-W√ºrttemberg Foundation. The foundation is providing a total of four million euros to support research ideas from the fields of Neurotechnology, Neuronal Computing and Neuronally-inspired Robotics in order to do justice to the increasing importance of these fields. Read more CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" The DFG-funded collaborative research center ‚ÄúRobust Vision ‚Äì Inference Principles and Neural Mechanisms‚Äù ( CRC 1233 ) studies basic principles of biological and machine vision, and is a close collaboration between scientists from neuroscience and computational vision. Read more MICrONS Although neuroscience has inspired many elements of artificial neuronal networks, the mammalian visual system is still markedly different from current state-of-the-art deep neural networks in terms of its circuit architecture, robustness, and ability to learn. Two groups at the Bernstein center (Bethge, Sinz) are part of a multi-university consortium funded by the MICrONs program within the Obama BRAINinitiative. Read more ITN "switchBoard" switchBoard is an Innovative Training Network (ITN) funded by the European Commission's Horizon 2020 programme under the Marie Curie Actions 2015-2019 involving several of the BCCN-associated groups. Read more About us At the Bernstein Center T√ºbingen, scientists from various disciplines, including theoretical and experimental neurobiology, machine learning, and medicine, collaborate in order to analyze the basis of inference processes in the brain. In particular, a main research goal is to understand the coordinated interaction of neurons durin