her transportation options: Train Most trains arriving and departing from T√ºbingen are regional trains. Thus, you‚Äôll most likely be switching from a high speed train in Stuttgart (the closest big city) to a regional train from Stuttgart to T√ºbingen. However, these trains are quite efficient and run on a regular schedule. Plane The closet airport to T√ºbingen is the Stuttgart Airport. Thankfully, the airport is well-connected to many European destinations. They also have one long-haul flight from Atlanta. Once you land in Stuttgart, you can easily take a train, bus, or car directly to T√ºbingen. Bus The most direct way to T√ºbingen is via a bus. There are local buses and long-distance buses that will take you to the town center. The local buses run within the region of Stuttgart and can connect you directly from Stuttgart‚Äôs city center as well as the airport to T√ºbingen. The long-distance buses connect T√ºbingen with many cities and towns both within, and outside of, Germany. History of T√ºbingen As students make up one-third of T√ºbingen‚Äôs population, the history of the town is very much integrated into the university‚Äôs history. The university is one of the oldest in all of Europe ‚Äì it was founded in 1477 and is considered one of the five classical universities of Germany (along with Heidelberg ‚Äì where I did my master‚Äôs degree). The city is especially known for its Germanic studies program, theology program, law school, and science programs (including medicine). DNA was actually discovered at the University of T√ºbingen in 1868. During the Third Reich, the University of T√ºbingen was unfortunately at the forefront of legitimizing Nazi beliefs and programs. The university employed very few Jews even before 1933 and any Jews still working at the university were forced into early retirement. Additionally, almost 1,200 sterilizations were performed at the University of T√ºbingen‚Äôs hospital. On a lighter note, the university has an impressive alumni roster. Famous students and professors include Johannes Kepler, Horst K√∂hler (President of Germany), Friedrich H√∂lderlin, Pope Benedict XVI, Friedrich Shelling, and Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel as well as 12 Nobel Laureates. Chocolate Festival in T√ºbingen I never had the opportunity to see T√ºbingen in wintertime and had eagerly been waiting to attend the annual international chocolate festival ! To be honest, the festival was a bit of a disappointment. However, how much of a disappointment could it actually be with so much chocolate everywhere?! I thought the festival would be a bit more interactive. Instead, it was mainly just stalls with different chocolate companies selling their goods. However, I‚Äôm never one to turn down chocolate üòâ Let‚Äôs be honest though, I took fullllll advantage of the mulled wine with chocolate in it. It was absolutely freezing and what‚Äôs better than chocolate warming you up? Mulled wine, that‚Äôs what‚Äôs better üòâ Double winning with chocolate and mulled wine together üòâ Also, I attended the festival with my friend Christina (she‚Äôs a fellow blogger over at Happy To Wander and her photos/blog are to die for‚Ä¶). We had never met in person prior to meeting at the festival so it was either going to be really awesome or really awkward. Thank goodness it was the former ‚Äì I felt like we had been friends for years and it was great to swap blogging/traveling/Germany stories with her! Snowy Weather in T√ºbingen More exciting than the chocolate festival itself was waking up Sunday morning to the city blanketed in fresh, powdery snow. I can‚Äôt speak for southern Germany but Hamburg has had an unusually snowy winter! Maybe I‚Äôm a crazy person but I much prefer cold weather over hot weather any day of the week ‚Äì bonus points if snow accompanies the cold weather. I felt like I was in a winter wonderland snow globe! Where to Eat & Drink in T√ºbingen T√ºbingen actually has an impressive food and cafe culture. Obviously, it‚Äôs nice to take advantage of all the cafes during summertime when they have outdoor seating but there are still plenty of opportunities for a good drink and a good meal in wintertime. Here are some of my favorites! Gasthaus B√§ren | Schmiedtorstra√üe 3 This restaurant serves the most delicious Swabian food for an absolute steal. Christina and I happened upon this restaurant and it was full of locals. The tables are close together and the noise level is quite high, but you can‚Äôt help but absolutely love it! We went for lunch and thought it was perfect. Zum Alten Fritz | Gartenstra√üe 13 We were both craving Italian food and stumbled across this restaurant as one of the top Italian recommendations. The interior makes you feel like you‚Äôre underground in a cave and the food is equally delicious. Also, not a bad selection of wine at all üòâ Cafe Tangente Jour | M√ºnzgasse 17 While studying abroad in T√ºbingen, I must have come to this cafe at least once a week for their delicious tomato soup. The cafe is in a great location and the food was always so light and fresh! Collegium | Lange G. 8 Another really great cafe in the middle of town that serves reasonably priced food, beer, coffee, and everything in between! Piccolo Sole d‚ÄôOro | Metzgergasse 39 Definitely one of the best places in T√ºbingen for beer, wine, cocktails, coffee, and small snacks. The interior is cozy and authentic, and it is definitely one of the most popular spots to hang out for a drink (whether a mid-afternoon coffee, evening glass of wine, or weekend beer). T√ºbinger Wurstk√ºche | Am Lustnauer Tor 8 This is the ‚Äúit‚Äù place to go in T√ºbingen for traditional German/Swabian food! The menu is long and authentic, and the interior is just what you would imagine a German restaurant looking like inside. Liquid Bar / Die Kelter | Schmiedtorstra√üe 17 I found this restaurant/bar/lounge right at the end of my study abroad in T√ºbingen and I was kicking myself for not finding it sooner! While you can eat here, I came for the cocktails which are top-notch and highly recommended. Things To Do in T√ºbingen in Wintertime Market Square and City Hall (Marktplatz and Rathaus) The majestic T√ºbingen City Hall was built in the mid-15th century as a three-level building (the fourth level was added about 75 years later). The astronomical clock at the top of the building was installed in 1511 and still functions ‚Äì showing the various locations of stars and the phases of the moon. While the T√ºbingen Market Square is taken full advantage of during the summer months (outdoor cafes and restaurants dot the entire Market Square), the winter months still add a level of charm, especially when snowing. Not only can you enjoy the T√ºbingen Chocolate Festival but weekly events and markets occur here year-round. Hohent√ºbingen Castle (Schloss Hohent√ºbingen) The most defining feature in T√ºbingen, Hohent√ºbingen Castle rises high above the old town area of the city. The castle was first mentioned almost 1,000 years ago. While it has undergone multiple renovations and reconstructions, most of the modern-day castle is from the 1600s, reflecting the Renaissance style of the time period. Besides being a local tourist attraction, the castle is also home to numerous University of T√ºbingen institutions and collections as well as a museum. Regardless of the weather, Hohent√ºbingen Castle provides great views of the entire city of T√ºbingen. Stiftskirche (Collegiate Church) The Collegiate Church is not just one of the main features in T√ºbingen but also has an important place in Reformation history. Built in 1470, it was one of the first churches to convert to Protestantism after Martin Luther‚Äôs Reformation. Interestingly enough, the church still has several Catholic features including patron saints and a shrine dedicated to the Virgin Mary. Regardless of the weather, this church is open year-round and a nice place to hide away on a cold, snowy day! H√∂lderlin‚Äôs Tower and Ederhard‚Äôs Bridge (H√∂lderlinturm and Ederhardsbr√ºcke) The postcard photo of T√ºbingen, Eberhard‚Äôs Bridge provides the iconic view of T√ºbingen. Regardless of the time of year, this view is absolutely stunning ‚Äì between the falling snow in winter and the Stockerkahn (similar to punting) races in the summertime. As this bridge is directly between the main train/bus station and the old town of T√ºbingen, it‚Äôs impossible to miss it! Located at one end of these beautiful, colorful houses is H√∂lderlin‚Äôs Tower. He lived there from 1807 to his death in 1843. Diagnosed with schizophrenia and having had a mental breakdown, he was taken in by Ernst Zimmer, a carpenter that owned the tower and was enamoured with H√∂lderlin‚Äôs writing. H√∂lderlin spent the rest of his life living and working on the first floor of this tower. Neckar Island (Neckarinsel) A beautiful spot for a short walk along the river, Neckar Island is a small piece of tranquility located right in T√ºbingen. While I was visiting, the entire island was covered in snow, making my walk feel like a winter wonderland. It also gives a wonderful view of all the colorful houses lining the bank of the Neckar. In the summertime, people gather on the island to sunbathe or watch the local Stockerkahn boat races. Old Town T√ºbingen (Altstadt T√ºbingen) While quite small and doable in a day (or even an afternoon), the old town area of T√ºbingen is not to be missed! Some of my favorite streets include Burgsteige (leading up to the castle), Judengasse (the former Jewish quarter during the Middle Ages), Lange Gasse, and M√ºnzgasse. Make sure to also explore and visit the university‚Äôs original buildings interspersed throughout the old town area. Final Thoughts on T√ºbingen in Wintertime I can‚Äôt believe it took me so long to visit T√ºbingen in wintertime ‚Äì why didn‚Äôt I do this sooner?! While I have so many wonderful and fond memories of T√ºbingen in the summer months, there really is something magical and fairy tale-like about th