 level. The R. Neckar is navigable between Plochingen and Mannheim. Ports are located in Plochingen, Stuttgart, Heilbronn and Mannheim. Just as the Rhine, the R. Neckar is subject to numerous uses. The middle and lower course of the Neckar is impounded. The many uses of the river have fundamentally modified the ecology of the water course. Only the upper course of the R. Neckar has largely preserved its natural character. external link: Baden-Wuertemberg: http://www.wrrl.baden-wuerttemberg.de History of the ICPR Secretariat of the ICPR Did you know ... that, thanks to the R. Neckar, Father Rhine is supported by a ‚Äúwild lad‚Äú? The name of the Neckar is of Celtic origin and means wild water or wild lad. It is derived from the primeval European word ‚Äúnik‚Äù meaning to dash off. ICPR ‚Äì International Commission for the Protection of the Rhine Office Address Kaiserin-Augusta-Anlagen 15 D-56068 Koblenz Postal Address Postfach 20 02 53 D-56002 Koblenz Contact +49 (0) 261 / 942 52 - 0 +49 (0) 261 / 942 52 - 52 sekretariat(at)iksr.de Information Home ICPR Topics EU Directives Events Documents/Archive Visitor centers Contact Imprint Data privacy Disclaimer on accessibility ICPR About us History Reasons for the cooperation Conceiving cooperation The Berne Convention Increasing confidence The Chlorides Convention The turning point: the Sandoz accident Integration and example The Rhine in a European context Organisation Members Observers States IGOs NGOs Cooperations Secretariat Legal basis Convention Objectives Sustainability Conferences of ministers Rhine project non-target screening Background Participants and structure of the project Rhine 2040 Ecology Water quality Floods Low water Rhine 2020 Ecological successes Success water quality Successes of extreme discharges Predecessor programmes Rhine Action Programme Salmon 2020 Action Plan on Floods Topics Rhine Water cycle Varying runoff Thermal exchange processes Sub-basins Alpine Rhine / Lake Constance Aar High Rhine Up